The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to belong to the older generation, they find no work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are quite rarely affected by this fate."
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help with work and give birth to children," a nun describes the situation that takes care of more than one hundred women in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a special home, who were ejected by their communities.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure."
And for this reason, issued a brochure that is intended to prevent the "witch's persecution".
But the matter has a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper DerStandard pointed out of the dilemma of written enlightenment.
However, being accused of witchcraft is also commonplace in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they doused them with petroleum and simply set them on fire.
The BBC also reported on this incident.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointings.
This is after the group tried to "expel an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" support the people here without regard to their education.
"The Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Eaters of human souls are a danger in the past as they are today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, the Gambian president himself has been involved in the past year.
"President Yahya Jammeh sparked a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, as they allegedly played a part in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To this end, he called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguard, forcibly kidnapped women and men indiscriminately from Gambian villages and brought them to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the incarcerated people were forced to drink an absud from plants with hallucinogenic effect, but which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
It was only because of international pressure that the nearly a thousand prisoners were released.
