The architects saw it - the office also has a kindergarten
The office building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings come, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for his company mini kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees (inside) are of the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the project managers and architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the ability to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers and architects have made it easier to reconcile their demanding profession and child welfare.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees (inside) of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they succeeded in attracting funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operations Programme from the European Social Fund and from the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (grants of 2, 8 million CZK) could be procured the necessary facilities and equipment and for a period of 2 years is provided for qualified personnel and for the operation.
After the use of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the Minikindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are taken care of by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can be attended by children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but the day takes place over several children.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the program content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting program of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic findings to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can always take a look at the children and so the stress of the delayed pick-up of the children from a faraway kindergarten is eliminated.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design was thus among the Czech companies that offer clear benefits in the recruitment of new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof seems like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are ripped-up fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile shards and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style by Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living things.
Only on closer inspection does one notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well thought-out order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intertwined shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Shaft-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and strips.
The house Batlló in the district of Eixample on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batlló apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Especially on its drawing board, the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the real estate and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in Park Güell, where other works by Antoni Gaudí are located.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, in turn, called it the "yawning house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the very top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house at that time with venting channels and typical fireplaces.
A little bizarrely, her 45-degree inclination already seems.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all building regulations at that time and was by no means deterred by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified by the result at the time of completion that they demanded a remedy.
The councillors also came across, among other things, that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the request of the district in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted an application for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery in the 2. Stock was a company salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building passes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could comfortably chat without having to do without a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new facade, the house was given a rather unusual roof and two other floors by Gaudí’s conversion.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the atriums.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply used the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sunlight.
The house Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this is quite a profitable business, the visits were retained, and they were also extended to other common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for the visit to the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed frame? Women have different desires than men
Not the greatest bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
In the selection, many things play a role - the weight, the size, the state of health and last but not least the gender of the sleeper.
Just as important is the interior, in which the mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house where there is no regular heating, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "warm up."
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough venting channels in the core and are also lying on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not excluded that it forms under their mold.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will be difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Are probably all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can no longer sleep properly here."
"For their worn-out shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (Memory Foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I recommend these, among other things, to sugar-sick people who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can poorly receive the "information" from the joints and the skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I got many hockey players years ago, but also other customers, these mattresses with Visco foam (Memory Foam).
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer, among other things, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don't necessarily have to be a famous hockey player to appreciate the benefits of the Visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it nestles on the warm body.
Nowhere does it press, at night you don't roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (volume).
When choosing the size of the mattress, you should still add the length of the soles of the feet to the body size, so approx. 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman who are about 180 cm tall need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm lying width, together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
Half of the comfort and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the guild master of the upholsterers and interior decorators, who has devoted herself for years to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and also presents this topic at technical schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grates at different heights and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with feather skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be accounted for by the mould layer and the fine upholstery.
"By hand or when you sit down, you must not feel the feathers in any case," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Full-padded beds with mattress and underlayment such as mixed Siam twins have nothing to do in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and you cannot wash the cover, which is already common today.
And since you lose between 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve) after five to seven years.
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a service life of up to 25 years, even a lifetime guarantee for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily peeled off and washed.
