More and more parents want people surveillance devices to have the kids under control
The fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented for the search for cars, can just as well locate people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently with the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have terrified the fall of the missing Anička and so they are looking for means and ways to better protect their children.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood that tragedy will occur," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that it can come to the misuse of such devices on a case-by-case basis, for example, if you put it in someone's pocket without them knowing about it, but we have not had such a case so far."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
