In the period from 1994-2009, she followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer with her colleagues in Britain, but at the same time 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, for men to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which form in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chair of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was fleetingly aware of this study, but that he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven" so far.
