In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October poll.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (s. Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been around approx. 6% is growing, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year's sharp slump, such a trend can be seen.
Yet only half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, which lowers the regional average (e.g. Chart 2).
Ca. 44% of respondents said they are satisfied with their country's democratic practice. That’s as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
About 34% trust their country's congress and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and. 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
That this continued even during the Great Depression is possibly because Latin American countries experienced only a short period of recession and have recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again by 32% this year.)
But from country to country there are strong differences in sentiment (s. Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in widespread progress thinking.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the poll began, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than in unemployment (s. diagram 5).
Ca. 31% say either they themselves or a family member have been the victim of a crime last year. But compared to 38% last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic output is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market economies: approx. 71% of respondents nationally said that the private sector is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (p. Diagram 6).
Ca. 58% explained that only the market economy can bring progress to their land, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have retained this view (and 80% are in favor of a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizes many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared with 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most countries in Central America, on the other hand, see the most influential country in the U.S., taking on this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua from Venezuela.
An election slouch
No one had expected the elections on 28. November in Haiti would be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of the election workers who rushed to the aid of the battered country.
Crowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballots in the gutter, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were just part of the problems.
Polling stations opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless by the earthquake in January, roamed around in search of a choice.
Some eventually gave up altogether.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected frontrunners, demanded the cancellation of election results due to alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests across the country.
Still, Edmond Mulet, the head of the U.N. mission in Haiti, described the election "as quite good in many respects."
According to a cautious statement from observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which is supposedly committed to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will the preliminary results on 7. Announce December.
The expected runoff election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first-lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity lawsuit.
If Jude Célestin, who finds little or no approval among the voters, declares the winner of the run-off election from the election authority, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of earthquake victims still live in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting by a lack of organization.
Shortly before the election began, approx. 250,000 IDs needed for election have not yet been issued.
There's a lot at stake.
The donor countries regard a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves agree.
Secretly to the middle
In the weeks after her husband's sudden death, Argentina's president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that drove her popularity rate up 20 points to over 50%. That's the highest level since her election in 2007.
Whether this will help her to re-elect next year, however, depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs of this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also steered economic policy after his wife's election, frequently set out budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenue at their own discretion.
On paper, the Fernández administration lost the majority in Congress last year.
Yet the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on 27. October led to further quarrels.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling Peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
Yet after chaotic sessions (where one parliamentarian punched another in the face and others accused the government of bribery) Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
"I will not discuss this," the president said.
The 2010 budget now also applies to the next year, which gives the president even more opportunity to spend money at her own discretion.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and wage demands of the unions - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction to be his main goals, rather than the inflation cut.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector and cleaned up the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently highlighted official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández take a more moderate path now?
She has called the private sector and union leaders for talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be limited to 18% next year.
High world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
Yet inflation undermined the growth spurp by a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina to the rest of the world in terms of finance.
Earlier this year, the government struck an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country's earlier debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the donors from the Paris Club, to whom they ca. $6.7 billion owes.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is customary elsewhere.
However, last month, Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund will provide "technical support" in the creation of a new national consumer price index. It looks like this is the first step towards cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active even without her husband's support after her term ends.
If so, she needs the support of the middle class, which has largely had enough of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy that has been shown to it will have ebbed away.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to quietly overturn many of her husband's political decisions.
Weak applause for China
Taiwan's voters are slowly approaching a closer connection to the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother beyond the strait?
On the 27. November more than 7.5 million voters, which is 70% of all eligible voters, set out to elect mayors and city councillors in the five city districts. This is seen as a broad assessment by President Ma Ying-jeou.
By building groundbreaking business relations, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma himself is a symbol of relations with the mainland. His policy has permanently changed the relationship with the Chinese motherland for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but barely.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) represents three of the five mayors, it did not receive a majority.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which advocates greater Taiwan independence, received nearly 50% of the vote, which received KMT 45%.
In a presidential election, this would have meant problems for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party's share of votes has been around about. 8% fell.
For the first time, the DPP even moved into the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election, the usual incidents in Taiwan, such as truck convoys with riot makers, flag-waving mass removals and only scantily clothed dancers, occurred.
There was even the obligatory, mysterious attempted murder.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech on a KMT candidate on the eve of the election,
When a man from the crowd shot him in the face. Lien was wounded and a bystander killed.
Bizarrely, it is not clear whether the shooter wanted to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Separately, the attack has affected the election, according to Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the DPP, and put the DPP in a bad light, which has given the KMT more votes.
China may have been the biggest winner of the campaign.
Remarkably, relations with the mainland were not addressed.
Instead, candidates debated plans on social housing and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their de facto independence and reject China's military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to focus on its relations with the government in Beijing.
But this time the DPP also avoided stoking the anti-Chinese feelings too much.
She responded to the new awareness that Taiwan's economy cannot survive without China.
For his part, he wants to be confirmed that the majority of Taiwanese support his China policy.
The government in Beijing will continue to pursue its strategy of luring Taiwan back to the community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
It certainly also wants political integration. But the most important thing first.
It would rather wait until after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has since reinvented itself.
Two years ago, she was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was in prison for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he vehemently advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai's reign, a new generation of moderate politicians developed and the DPP is fighting for the voices of the working people and the youth.
Tsai found great approval as the presidential candidate of the DPP, like Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything it can to show that she, too, is capable of building close ties with Beijing.
Tsai is planning a think tank as a point of contact between the DPP and China. However, this requires unprejudiced discussions.
Tsai publicly stated that her party offers a "trustworthy alternative" to Mas's rash approach to China.
Chen seems very upset about this change.
From his cell, he declared that the candidates of the DPP had done better to insist on Taiwan's independence.
He even urged the pragmatist Su to forgo the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen's interference, the DPP is struggling to elect its possible candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
The values are poor, despite the rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to run their election campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the ever-increasing gap between rich and poor.
According to a KMT spokesman, he will redesign his cabinet as well as the local facilities.
The strong appearance of the DPP suggests that Taiwan only advocates a reapproach to a limited extent.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "there is already no turning back."
