Arsenic-resistant microbe could allow new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria, which can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
“This organism has two options.”
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"That makes it very special, even though it's almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California's Mono Lake grows even further even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible," said the co-author of the report, Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can set in motion with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements', which in our opinion are absolutely vital, are not necessarily firmly predetermined," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake due to high arsenic levels.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes that are exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly based on the fact that it behaves chemically similarly to phosphorus."
“This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other.”
"But the difference is so great that arsenic is different from phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smudges virtually everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, is not new to the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic. But so far, there has been no working example.
Arsenic occurred more frequently in the early Earth years, she says, that's why science has assumed early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may also have developed differently than in the early Earth age," according to Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research work was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
Other stolen exhibition dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four exhibition dogs stolen in front of a Bellflower motel were found Thursday, according to the Los Angeles County Sheriff's statement.
The four exhibition dogs - two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis - disappeared on Tuesday when unknowns stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van where the animals were housed outside a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, according to authorities statements.
Two of the dogs were discovered Wednesday afternoon, and the last two Wednesday night, explains Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is that the dogs are well up," Whitmore said.
"They're in good condition."
"They were returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not provide specifics on the location of the dogs, nor about the circumstances that led to their discovery.
"The investigation is still ongoing."
"We don't want to say more about that," Whitmore explains.
"We're tracking some tracks."
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available for information on Thursday.
They took their two dogs in reception Wednesday afternoon at a district animal shelter in Downey.
Representatives of the sheriff found the van and the two dogs in different locations in Compton.
The Akitas - Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old bitch - were unharmed, according to authorities statement.
Yet the Corgis Bunny and Peter, who Rickard and Peek wanted to introduce this week on behalf of their Japanese owners at the competition, remained missing until Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in town this weekend because of the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach because Trace was scheduled to take part in the contest.
As Peek told the Times on Wednesday, the other dogs should take part in other competitions on the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show.
Southern California is a stop on the couple's nearly month-long tour from dog show to dog show.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked in at the motel.
They frequently stay in motels and park their van in front of their room window.
They took three other dogs - a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier and a Brittany - with them to their motel room.
The thick-fured Akitas and Corgis stayed in the van because it was cooler there.
They left the window a gap wide open so the dogs had fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported their car stolen at 6:00 a.m. on Tuesday.
Peek promised anyone who could give a clue to the Corgis a finder's wage. The animals were implanted with microchips for identification.
On Thursday, it was not yet clear whether a finder's wage would be paid.
The lion is again roaring after court approval of the MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainties, MGM finally got the green light for a new start.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially blessed the "prepared" credit plan to pay off the $5 billion debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company for new movies and television shows.
According to Thursday's statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so nothing stands in the way of the restart of MGM led by Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment. Barber and Birnbaum will preside over the somewhat slimmed-down studio as chief executive.
The number of employees is from over 400 to approx. 320 lowered.
For MGM, Chapter 11 will not actually take effect until JPMorgan Chase has completed a planned $500 million bond to finance the new MGM productions.
At the moment, a consortium of the investment bank, which itself contributes $75 million, is managing the company. Funding is expected to be in place by mid-December.
The restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 with the order to the investment bank Moelis & Co, the company management, which struggled with interest payments of $300 million/year, to help solve its financial problems.
In August, managing director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert who became known through his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper's efforts to resolve the financial worries of MGM and pay out the studio's more than 140 dides lasted longer than expected.
After months of discussion, the parties decided at the end of 2009 to offer the company for sale.
But the auction attracted few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, it all started all over again when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by creditors after months of debate and internal disputes in late October.
If MGM has officially weathered the bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multi-million dollar bonus for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, amounts to $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 a month for the management of the company, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM. This year, the studio released only one film and created an annual plan of seven or eight films to hit theaters in early 2012.
They are also planning two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio needs a separate bond of between $265 million to $275 million for its financial stake in these two films, which are to be created under the direction of Peter Jackson.
The investor Carl Icahn, who. 18% of the MGM loan funded, attempted a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
But the last negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any result.
