Can courtesy connect the divider?
After a campaign of swear words and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the battle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and top Congress did not bring a breakthrough on the big issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called "lame duck session," the session at the end of a government term in which no decisions are made.
After all that you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather a blank episode of a partisan point collecting.
The public meeting of the President's deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months gives rise to mutual respect, obscuring the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
That's barely enough to claim it's a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - in which one demands from the other sign of cooperation and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, Tuesday's meeting itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to be expected to quickly change the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election has made Washington a mild vote for at least a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the "Ethics and Public Policy Center."
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections create partisan passions that die again.
And that's a good thing."
On some issues, especially those that are on the agenda of the "lame duck session," Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one advocates that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or even all, whether it is temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise on the increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment workers support.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
Yet William Glaston of the Brookings Insitution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation of the parties if the new 112. Congress will be convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - which leads courtesy to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening from today until 2012, as a pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have much to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
How worried Republican leaders may also be about them pokering too high, they know they need to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and override health care reform.
These party lines are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include a tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of government expenditure.
Vice-chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so much to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that these can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are very much struggling to even get close to that number.
The greatest resistance can be found in the elected representatives of the panel, since there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise on financial issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes and the health care system, later followed by a period of greater two-party cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public reaction.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek the compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
Seen in this way, the courtesy that is being displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
