On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of the former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of the Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible, who has summoned the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefinition of the euro.
Germany occupies a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - , supported by a large part of public opinion, approx. 50% of the population.
The third: A transformation of the euro in accordance with German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the suspension of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. That's why there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
That was the first sign of drifting apart between what Germany felt was necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was heavily criticised. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, Merkel comes out in the last days of October with a clear position. It calls for reform of the European Union's agreements to allow the rescue of a country while requiring private lenders to bear some of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European as it drove the Irish crisis and everything following.
But their proposal, though somewhat sweetened, was adopted. In the coming months, we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to cross it.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - there will no longer be the old functioning of the euro from this date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the infringing countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector will have to cover a portion of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was cited by Spain in boom times, simply will not be tolerated.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It's not just about driving the government deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do in these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will turn into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities we are offered by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the discussion with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in-house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything would change about that.
Among the possibilities considered, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of little serious countries, cannot be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it has warned us.
Sport and rule circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The allegedly instigated by two players of Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) exclusion in the match from 23. November against the Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink to be spilled over whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed in this sport rules.
Part of the debate surrounding the case presented goes back to the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who, in his anthem, pretends nobleness and honor and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role in the process, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this not explicitly prohibited by the statutes of conduct contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a rule circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the infringing players getting an unjustified benefit from the counterteam. That didn't happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of the Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by wrong play or bypass, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly in order to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the indiscribes pulled out of the intentional fouls.
Here it should be emphasized that the rival was neither put in a less favorable position nor advantages for the game played were expected, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, since the team could eventually also retire. In addition, players will receive a sanction with this procedure and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which they are eliminated less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation with one card.
This is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions to make the greatest possible benefit from the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they were more likely to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or fleeing from it without a penalty.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the rule environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic was created as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of provoked rule transmission.
The harm inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
