Global plan to renew lighting
The UN proposed a plan in Cancun yesterday to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs) equivalent to nearly one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be realized to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments of the industrialized countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the CFC released to the earth due to the lighting if the white-glowing bulbs, which so far still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better yet, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the worldwide fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major exhaust emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, one would still have to deduct 5 Gt from this balance to stabilize the climate increase of 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact phosphors, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs this energy requirement is reduced again by two times.
The compact phosphor bulbs average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company, incidentally, has taken part in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which conveys a hint of the savings possibilities of the exchange plan, which is to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new light bulbs give off very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact phosphor bulbs have reserves, since they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in the developing countries, unless the producers provide an acceptance point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact phosphor bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit substantially more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars annually on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
