Specifically, the total of French support for developing countries may remain stable (or decrease) - France is presupposing to comply with its commitment to the "new and additional" funding.
Another crucial element is the breakdown in donations and loans.
There is no rule on this yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, are €1 borrowed as equivalent with €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to be justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects linked to emission containment based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that is being taken as the equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the investor country should be credited as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking out 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of it.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) are making 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 on the fulfilment of their obligations, France will give just 10 cents and understand this to be a comparable stake.
Beautiful Hokuspokus!
All in all, France is operating with a double hoax in its fast-start financing: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros in the process.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once EU internally (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely fooling...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this is not going to be the case.
Be that as it may, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of premature funding.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its type of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equalizing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (a different, decisive and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of "computability" or the type of accounting of his loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive in the disputes as it is with other things.
So hope is based on the new environment minister, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast-launch and its vision of "computability" as well as the use of loans would inherently raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years old occupies 81 different chemical substances over the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "do not represent a statistically significant value given the low number of samples analysed, but represent the illustration character of the issue covered," had bought the food usually consumed within four, from a child about ten years old with meals, plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - were examined, as well as sweets from laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safely carciogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrinine disturbing factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if, in the approximate totality of cases, the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded, this survey is very well removed from the fact that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine interference factor is worrying," the association notes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, where the study has found traces of an insecticide strictly banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the chopping steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were also peppered.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have brought to light the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined, chemical residues was the "richest," and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unencumbered.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is likely to be undervalued," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "given the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilization diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had identified reference to the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables, which are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
